      <section id="how-to-apply">
        <h2>How to Apply This: A Complete Weekly Review Protocol</h2>
        <p>The following protocol executes the five core review elements in approximately 25 to 35 minutes. It is designed to be performed at a fixed time each week — Friday afternoon or Sunday evening are the most common choices — and to be executable even under low-motivation conditions.</p>

        <StepsList steps={[
          {
            number: 1,
            title: "Schedule the review and protect it as a non-negotiable appointment",
            description: "Choose a fixed weekly time for the review — the same time every week — and block it in your calendar as a recurring appointment with the same priority as an external meeting. Friday between 3 and 4 PM works well for most professionals because it allows the week to be fully processed before the weekend and the coming week to be opened with clarity. Sunday evening works well for those who prefer to begin the week with full clarity rather than ending the previous week with it. The specific time matters less than the consistency: the review derives its power from being performed every week without exception, not from being performed at the optimal moment."
          },
          {
            number: 2,
            title: "Capture and process all inboxes — physical and digital",
            description: "Begin by processing every collection point: email inbox (process to zero or to a clear next action for each item), physical inbox or desk (process every loose paper, note, and object), notes app (review and assign next actions to every captured item), voicemails and messages, and any other collection point where inputs accumulate. For each item, make one of four decisions: do it now if it takes under two minutes, assign it a next action and project home if it requires more, delegate it with a waiting-for note, or trash it. Do not organize without deciding. The goal is that by the end of this step, every input in every collection point has been processed to a clear decision."
          },
          {
            number: 3,
            title: "Review the calendar: past week and coming two weeks",
            description: "Scan the past week's calendar for any commitments, conversations, or events that generated tasks or follow-ups that were not captured during the week. Scan the coming two weeks for any appointments that require preparation, any conflicts that need to be resolved, and any open scheduling decisions that need to be made. Add any captured items to your task system with clear next actions. This calendar review typically surfaces three to five items per week that would otherwise remain as open loops until the deadline made them urgent — which is exactly the stress-generating, reactive pattern the weekly review is designed to prevent."
          },
          {
            number: 4,
            title: "Review project and next action lists: confirm currency",
            description: "Scan every active project to confirm that each has a clear, specific next physical action assigned. A project without a next action is a stalled project — it has no mechanism for forward movement until someone notices the stall and adds one. This review step is the maintenance function that keeps the external trusted system current and reliable. If every project has a next action and every next action reflects the current state of the project, the system is functioning. If not — if some projects are vague, some next actions are outdated, some commitments have changed — update them now. This step typically takes five to ten minutes and prevents the system degradation that makes people abandon their task management tools."
          },
          {
            number: 5,
            title: "Complete the weekly reflection: three questions, three minutes",
            description: "Answer these three questions in writing — brief answers, not essays: What went well this week and why? What did not go as planned, and what was the root cause? What is the single most important thing I would do differently next week? The Di Stefano research shows that written reflection produces stronger performance improvement than unwritten review. The three-question format ensures that the reflection covers both positive and negative experience — capturing successes for replication and failures for correction — while remaining brief enough to be completed without resistance. Write the answers in a dedicated weekly review log, not a disposable note. The accumulating log becomes a record of your own performance patterns over time, which is the raw material for the most valuable long-term insights the review produces."
          },
          {
            number: 6,
            title: "Set your big three: the week's most important outcomes",
            description: "Identify the three most important outcomes for the coming week — not tasks, but outcomes. An outcome is the state of affairs that will exist when the most important work is done: not 'work on the project proposal' but 'complete the first draft of the project proposal.' Each outcome should be specific enough that you will know unambiguously whether it was achieved, and aligned with your 90-day priorities rather than merely the most urgent items in your inbox. Write these three outcomes prominently — in your planner, on a sticky note on your monitor, or as the header of your weekly task list. They are the navigational anchors that keep the week intentional when reactive demands attempt to colonize it."
          }
        ]} />
      </section>

      <section id="misconceptions">
        <h2>Common Misconceptions About the Weekly Review</h2>

        <h3>Misconception 1: "I do not have enough going on to need a weekly review"</h3>
        <p>
          This is the most common reason people do not establish a weekly review practice, and it reflects a misunderstanding of what the review is for. The weekly review is not primarily a task management tool for people with high complexity. It is a cognitive hygiene practice for anyone who carries commitments across a weekly time horizon — which is virtually everyone with a professional life, a family, or personal projects. The person with 15 active commitments benefits from closing 15 open loops each week. The person with 50 commitments benefits from closing 50. The cognitive relief from the open loop resolution scales with the number of loops, not with any threshold of "busyness." People who believe they have too little going on to need a weekly review are almost universally discovering, when they first perform one, that they had significantly more uncaptured open loops than they realized.
        </p>

        <h3>Misconception 2: "The weekly review is the same as weekly planning"</h3>
        <p>
          Weekly planning is a subset of the weekly review — the forward-looking priority-setting component. The full weekly review also includes the backward-looking reflection component and the open loop closure component that planning alone does not address. A purely forward-looking weekly planning session — "what will I do next week?" — without the capture-and-clarify process leaves the week's uncaptured commitments as active cognitive loads. Without the reflection component, it fails to convert the past week's experience into performance improvement. The weekly review is architecturally different from weekly planning: it is a complete system maintenance operation, not a scheduling session.
        </p>

        <h3>Misconception 3: "Skipping one week does not matter much"</h3>
        <p>
          A skipped weekly review is not a neutral event. It means one week's worth of uncaptured open loops remain in working memory, one week's worth of unprocessed inputs accumulate in all collection points, and one week's worth of priority drift goes uncorrected. The following week begins without the cognitive clarity that the review would have established, which increases the reactive, urgent-driven task selection that the review is designed to prevent. Most importantly, the skipped week establishes the behavioral precedent for skipping — the habit's consistency record is broken, and the identity evidence that "I am someone who does a weekly review" is weakened. Per James Clear's "never miss twice" principle, one skipped review is recoverable; two consecutive skips begin building a competing habit of not reviewing. The week after a skip is the most important week to perform the review regardless of how truncated it needs to be.
        </p>
      </section>

